{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A script to extract nodes from CC curves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 After extraction, the nodes can be edited individually, and the original curve can be restored with smooth ramps -- or even fancy new shapes -- using the "Connect nodes" script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script offers two modes, LFO and GRID, which can be toggled by right-clicking:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab LFO mode: The script tries to find LFO apex (maximum) and nadir (miinimum) CCs. This is useful for changing an existing LFO into a new LFO of the same rhythm, but with new ramp shapes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab GRID mode: In addition to find LFO nodes, the script will also extract CCs that are close to the grid spacing (without quantizing their positions to the grid). This is useful for smoothing an existing freehand-drawn curve, since the overall shape will not be changed.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The GRID mode is reminiscent of REAPER's built-in quantize functions, but has two important advantages: 1) the CC positions are not changed, and 2) CC are not overwritten by their neighbors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In both modes, moving the mouse left and right sets the grid and node spacing, and moving the mouse up and down sets the cut-off height of nodes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To use:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab select CC events from which to extract the nodes,\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab position mouse in lane,\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab press shortcut key, and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab use the mouse to change extraction parameters.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5)\tx360\tab To finish, left-click, press any keyboard key, or if the shortcut has been held down for more than half a second, simply release the key.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE EDITING SCRIPTS vs REAPER's LEFT-DRAG MOUSE MODIFIER ACTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" script resemble REAPER's own left-drag mouse modifier actions (such as "Draw CCs", "Arpeggiate", "Paint notes", etc), in that the scripts follow mouse movement and continue to run until the user stops the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the scripts are more advanced than the native actions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The scripts' functioning (such as the ramp shape or the channel of inserted CCs) can be tweaked while the script is running, using the mousewheel, mouse middle button and right button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whereas native actions can only be started and stopped by left-dragging and lifting the mouse button, the scripts be started and stopped in multiple ways, allowing a more customized and streamlined workflow.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Starting a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  To start and stop the script using a shortcut, you have two options: \line
      1) Two keystrokes: To start, press the shortcut key once *without holding the key down* and then press the same or any other key to stop;\line
      2) Press and hold: Press the shortcut key and hold it down for as long as the script should run. If the key is held down for more than one second, the script will terminate when the key is released.\line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
  (NOTE: In current versions of REAPER, actions can not be assigned to left-drag mouse modifiers, \line
         but the script will automatically detect a left-drag movement. To use left-drag, assign the script to a *double*-click mouse modifier.)\line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stopping a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left clicking while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left-dragging and lifting the left button after holding the button down for more than one second.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Pressing any key while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Releasing the shortcut key after holding it down for more than one second.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 RUNNING THE SCRIPT FROM THE TOOLBAR:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of the script depends on initial mouse position (similar to some of REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), the script cannot be run from a toolbar button.\line This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a "toolbar arming" feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" scripts therefore offer an alternative "toolbar arming" solution:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1  (I.e. the Run script is linked to a shortcut, while the individual Mouse editing scripts are linked to toolbar buttons.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or over the Actions list when the Mouse editing script starts (or, actually, anywhere else outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and its button will light up with the normal "activated" color.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab When the "Run" script is executed with its shortcut, it will run the armed Mouse editing script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By using this feature, each "Mouse editing" script does need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "Run" script needs to be linked to a shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP: The responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and edit takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of edit and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP 2: If the MIDI editor gets slow and jerky when a certain VST plugin is loaded, check for graphics driver incompatibility by disabling graphics acceleration in the plugin.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script allows multiple "Mouse editing" scripts to be run from a single (keyboard or mousewheel) shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The shortcut that is linked to this script will toggle start/stop any "Mouse editing" script that is armed in the toolbar.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 TOOLBAR ARMING\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of "Mouse editing" scripts depends on initial mouse position (similar to REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), these scripts cannot be run by mouse-clicking a toolbar button or the Actions list.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a "toolbar arming" feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "Mouse editing" scripts therefore offer an alternative, scripted, solution for toolbar arming:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run the script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel (or both) shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 (In other words, the Run script is linked to a shortcut, while the individual Mouse editing scripts are linked to toolbar buttons.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or over the Actions list when the Mouse editing script starts (or, actually, anywhere else outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and its button will light up with the normal "activated" color.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab When the "Run" script is executed with its shortcut, it will run the armed Mouse editing script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By using this feature, each Mouse editing script does need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "Run" script needs to be linked to a shortcut.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A multifunctional script for stretching and compressing MIDI events.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Depending on mouse position when the script starts, the script can: * stretch event positions (horizontally) to the mouse position, or * stretch event values (vertically) to the mouse position, or * compress/expand the lane boundaries with various types of curves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 STRETCH EVENTS:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is positioned {\i inside} a CC lane or the notes area when the script starts, it will only affect events in that individual lane. (After the script starts, the mouse may move out of the lane.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is positioned {\i outside} a CC lane when the script starts, i.e. over a lane divider or over the ruler area, and the mouse is moved left or right, the script will stretch selected events on {\i all} lanes together.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is positioned to the {\i right} of the selected events, it will stretch the right edge of event positions to the mouse position.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, if the mouse is positioned to the {\i left} of the selected events, it will stretch the left edge of event positions to the mouse position.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is positioned closer to the middle of the time range, and to the top [or bottom] of the CC's value range, it will stretch the top [or bottom] values up or down to the mouse position.\line (MIDI notes, as well as events that do not have CC values, such as Text or Sysex, can only be stretched left/right, not up/down.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When stretching top or bottom, right-click to toggle between one-sided stretching and symmetric stretching around the relative center of the selected events' value range.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 COMPRESS LANE:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is positioned over a lane divider when the script starts, and then moved up or down into the CC lane, the script will compress or expand the lane range. (Think of the movement as "dragging" the lane boudary up or down.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In this mode, event values are either scaled relative to the opposite lane boundary, or symmetrically relative to the absolute center and the lane. Right-click to switch between one-sided and symmetric compression.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script will draw the compression curve on the screen.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Compress mode is not yet available for the inline MIDI editor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE CONTROL:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Left-clicking terminates the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 While stretching, * flipping the mouse wheel will flip the selected CCs around. (If stretching horizontally, flips event positions; if vertically, flips values.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 While compressing, * the middle button toggles between a linear/power curve and a sine curve, * mouse wheel further tweaks the curve, and * the right button toggles the mode between 1-sided compression (from either the top or bottom) or symmetrical compression.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE EDITING SCRIPTS vs REAPER's LEFT-DRAG MOUSE MODIFIER ACTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" script resemble REAPER's own left-drag mouse modifier actions (such as "Draw CCs", "Arpeggiate", "Paint notes", etc), in that the scripts follow mouse movement and continue to run until the user stops the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the scripts are more advanced than the native actions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The scripts' functioning (such as the ramp shape or the channel of inserted CCs) can be tweaked while the script is running, using the mousewheel, mouse middle button and right button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whereas native actions can only be started and stopped by left-dragging and lifting the mouse button, the scripts be started and stopped in multiple ways, allowing a more customized and streamlined workflow.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Starting a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  (NOTE: To run the script, press the shortcut key *once* and do not hold the key.) \line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
  (NOTE: In current versions of REAPER, actions can not be assigned to left-drag mouse modifiers, \line
         but the script will automatically detect a left-drag movement. To use left-drag, assign the script to a *double*-click mouse modifier.)\line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stopping a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left clicking\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left-dragging and lifting the left button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Pressing any mouse modifier key (Ctrl/Cmnd, Alt, Shift or Win).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: If a shortcut has been assigned to the script, that same shortcut will toggle the script on/off. (NOTE: The first time that the script is stopped by its shortcut, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 RUNNING THE SCRIPT FROM THE TOOLBAR:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of the script depends on initial mouse position (similar to some of REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), the script cannot be run from a toolbar button.\line This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a "toolbar arming" feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" scripts therefore offer an alternative "toolbar arming" solution:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1  (I.e. the Run script is linked to a shortcut, while the individual Mouse editing scripts are linked to toolbar buttons.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or over the Actions list when the Mouse editing script starts (or, actually, anywhere else outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and its button will light up with the normal "activated" color.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab When the "Run" script is executed with its shortcut, it will run the armed Mouse editing script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By using this feature, each "Mouse editing" script does need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "Run" script needs to be linked to a shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP: The responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and editable takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of editable and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP 2: If the MIDI editor gets slow and jerky when a certain VST plugin is loaded, check for graphics driver incompatibility by disabling graphics acceleration in the plugin.\par}
}

