{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Select events in the MIDI editor's CC lanes by simply swiping the mouse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All events within the horizontal (time) range of mouse movement will be selected, and the mouse does not need to touch the CC bars.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is positioned over a CC lane when the script starts, only events in that lane will be selected.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is positioned over a CC lane divider when the script starts, events in all visible lanes will be selected.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the the mouse is not position over the MIDI editor piano roll, the script will arm itself, so that it can be called via the script "js_Run the 'Mouse editing' script that is selected in toolbar (link this to shortcut and mousewheel)".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE EDITING SCRIPTS vs REAPER's LEFT-DRAG MOUSE MODIFIER ACTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" script resemble REAPER's own left-drag mouse modifier actions (such as "Draw CCs", "Arpeggiate", "Paint notes", etc), in that the scripts follow mouse movement and continue to run until the user stops the script.\par}
