{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Starting a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  To start and stop the script using a shortcut, you have two options: \line
      1) Two keystrokes: To start, press the shortcut key once *without holding the key down* and then press the same or any other key to stop;\line
      2) Press and hold: Press the shortcut key and hold it down for as long as the script should run. If the key is held down for more than one second, the script will terminate when the key is released.\line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
  (NOTE: In current versions of REAPER, actions can not be assigned to left-drag mouse modifiers, \line
         but the script will automatically detect a left-drag movement. To use left-drag, assign the script to a *double*-click mouse modifier.)\line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stopping a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left clicking while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left-dragging and lifting the left button after holding the button down for more than one second.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Pressing any key while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Releasing the shortcut key after holding it down for more than one second.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 RUNNING THE SCRIPT FROM THE TOOLBAR:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of the script depends on initial mouse position (similar to some of REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), the script cannot be run from a toolbar button.\line This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
