\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Inserting events in the wrong channel is an all-too-easy mistake to make, particularly after switching the active track. With this new option, the user can switch to the correct channel by simply clicking a note or CC of the new track.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is intended to be similar to the built-in action "Option: Drawing or selecting a note sets the new note length" (but for channel instead of note length).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 NOTE: This script causes the following artefacts: ~ If an event in a {\i new} channel is selected by left-clicking on the event, the event can not be edited immediately; instead, the mouse button must be released first. (This can be a useful indicator that the active channel has been changed.) ~ While this script is running, it may interact with the manual settings of the MIDI editor's channel filter dropdown menu.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script can be linked to a toolbar button for easy starting and stopping.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 While activated, the toolbar button will light up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (The first time that the script is stopped, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Inserting events in the wrong MIDI channel is an all-too-easy mistake to make, particularly after switching the active track. If this option is activated, the default MIDI channel for new events\line will automatically be set to the channel of existing MIDI events in the newly active track, whenever the active take is switched.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the existing MIDI events in the track use more than one channel, the default channel will be set one of these channels, usually - but not always - the channel of the very first event in the take.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To find the channel, the script will first search through the newly active take itself to find MIDI events with usable channel info. If no such MIDI events are found (for example if the take is empty) the script will search through other takes in the same track.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If no MIDI events are found anywhere in the track, the script will check whether the track has any MIDI sends, and will use the MIDI send channel of the sends, if any.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (Therefore, by setting a MIDI send channel before drawing new MIDI events in the track, the send channel will act as the default channel for MIDI events in the track.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script can be linked to a toolbar button for easy starting and stopping.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 While activated, the toolbar button will light up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (The first time that the script is stopped, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When inserting CCs via scripts such as\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab js_Draw linear or curved ramps in real time\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab js_Insert linear or shaped ramps between selected CCs or pitches in lane under mouse\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab js_LFO Tool the user can choose whether redundant events (i.e. events with the same value as the preceding event) should be skipped.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script toggles the behavior of the above-mentioned scripts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (In previous versions of these scripts, the user had to edit the script file's USER AREA in order to change the behavior of the scripts. This is no longer necessary.)\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Removes redundant events from selected CCs in 7-bit CC, pitchwheel, channel pressure and program select lanes with a single click.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the USER AREA of the script (below the changelog), the user can customize the following options: (It may be useful to link different versions of the script to different shortcuts.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab lanes_from_which_to_remove: "all", "last clicked" or "under mouse"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab ignore_LSB_of_pitch: Ignore LSB when comparing pitchwheel events\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab only_analyze_selected_events: Ignore unselected events in the target lane\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 NOTE: If lanes_from_which_to_remove == "all", each 7-bit lane of 14-bit CCs will be analyzed separately. This will ensure maximum efficiency in removal of redundant events, but may cause 14-bit CCs to 'disappear' since MSB and LSB parts may be deleted separately.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two ways in which this script can be run:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab First, the script can be linked to its own shortcut key.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Second, this script, together with other "js_" scripts that edit the "lane under mouse", can each be linked to a toolbar button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab In this case, each script need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "js_Run the js_'lane under mouse' script that is selected in toolbar.lua" script needs to be linked to a keyboard shortcut (as well as a mousewheel shortcut).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Clicking the toolbar button will 'arm' the linked script (and the button will light up), and this selected (armed) script can then be run by using the shortcut for the aforementioned "js_Run..." script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab For further instructions - please refer to the "js_Run..." script.\sa180\sa180\par}
}

