{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script selects and deselects notes, based on a pattern that the user can draw in a GUI.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, the pattern can be drawn to select notes 1, 3 and 4 in a six-step pattern.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The length of the pattern as well as the steps that will be selected are determined by the user. (The maximum pattern length is 99 steps.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script offers two modes: "Step pattern" and "Measure division", which can be toggled by clicking on the "Mode" text in the GUI. In "Measure division" mode, notes are selected and deselected based on their beat positions in the measure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In Step pattern mode, notes that start within one grid length of each other are regarded as one unit (e.g. chord or glissando), and will be selected/deselected together.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 First, select the note on which the step pattern must be applied. (Of course, some of these notes will later be deselected by the script.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Then, run the script and draw the desired pattern - the note selection will be updated in real time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you need to work with a new set of notes, simply click the "Load new set of notes" text.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If no notes are selected when the script is started, the script will dim out the step pattern display, and wait for the user to load a new set of notes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To draw patterns that are longer than the initial size of the GUI, simply widen the GUI.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To toggle between the two modes, "Step pattern" and "Measure division", simply click the "Mode" text at the top of the GUI.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 NEW IN VERSION 1.20:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The user can freely edit CCs or velocities in the MIDI editor while a set of notes is loaded, without having to reload the notes after editing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the pitches or positions of the loaded {\i notes} are edited in the MIDI editor, it may confuse the script, but the script will try to add any {\i selected} and edited notes to the set of loaded, active notes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, if you change the pitch of some of the loaded notes, simply ensure that these notes are still selected when clicking in the GUI again, and these edited notes will remain loaded.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 TIP:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script works well with the "js_Deselect all notes outside time selection (from all takes).lua" script. Use the piano roll keys to select all notes in a range of pitches, and then run the Deselect script to limit the note selection to the time selection.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER does not provide native actions to select the channel for new events for the Inline MIDI Editor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By default, the MIDI channel is linked to the last-used settings in the (full, not inline) MIDI editor, for each item individually, and the user therefore has to open the full MIDI editor for each item, in order to change the channel.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script provides a dropdown list from which the active MIDI channel can quickly be selected, while working in the inline MIDI editor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Warnings:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab In items with multiple MIDI takes, it is possible that the script does not determine the current channel and filter settings correctly. Changing the filter and channel will still work.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Inline MIDI editors easily lose focus, and keyboard shortcuts will then inadvertently pass through to the Main section. Click in the inline editor after changing channel to re-focus the editor.\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script tilts and shifts selected events or down to make the leftmost and rightmost event values equal to the chased values on either side.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is useful for ensuring smooth transitions after editing the selected events.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script only affects events in the MIDI editor lane that is under the mouse cursor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each MIDI channel is handled separately.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script can be used in 7-bit CC lanes, 14-bit CC lanes, velocity, pitchwheel and channel pressure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 NOTE: The script currently only chases CCs in the active item, and can therefore not fit the selected CCs to other chased CCs in other items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To use:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab select MIDI events to be tilted,\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab position mouse in lane,\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab press shortcut key, and\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two ways in which this script can be run:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab First, the script can be linked to its own shortcut key. This is the standard method.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Second, this script, together with other "js_" scripts that edit the "lane under mouse", can each be linked to a toolbar button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab In this case, each script need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "js_Run the js_'lane under mouse' script that is selected in toolbar.lua" script needs to be linked to a keyboard shortcut (as well as a mousewheel shortcut).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Clicking the toolbar button will 'arm' the linked script (and the button will light up), and this selected (armed) script can then be run by using the shortcut for the aforementioned "js_Run..." script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab For further instructions - please refer to the "js_Run..." script.\sa180\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When the MIDI editor's active take is switched via the track list to a take that is out of view, the MIDI editor will automatically "Zoom to content". If the newly active MIDI take is very large, "Zoom to content" provides a nice overview of the entire item, so that the user can easily locate the relevant MIDI data. However, zooming in again can be a hassle.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, when opening multiple MIDI items simultaneously (with Preferences -> MIDI Editor -> Open all selected items), the MIDI editor will "zoom to content", trying to fit all the items into the viewport.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script is therefore intended to provide an easy, one-click action to zoom in, without requiring the user to change the note, time or loop selection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script can either zoom to the mouse position, ir to the edit cursor position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is over a part of the interface that has position info (i.e. the arrange view, the ruler, or the MIDI editor's "notes" or "cc" areas), the MIDI editor will zoom to the mouse position.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is positioned anywhere else (for example the "track list" area of the MIDI editor), the MIDI editor will scroll and zoom to the current position of the edit cursor. (Zooming to the edit cursor is particularly useful for returning to the last edit position, after inadvertently scrolling to a faraway item.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Simply move the mouse to the position that you want to edit, and press the linked shortcut or mouse modifier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the script's USER AREA, the user can change the number of measures that the script zooms to, and these modified scripts can be saved under different names and linked to different shortcuts or mouse modifiers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Warning\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script temporarily changes the loop region, so it may be safer to avoid running the script during playback or recording.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Provides a graphical interface for accessing the "SWS/S&M: Save/Restore displayed CC lanes..." actions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Requires the SWS extension.\par}
